		<!--serialsettings>9600 8 none 1 off</serialsettings-->

		<SINGLETON_ID>RoomJoin</SINGLETON_ID>

		<documentation>The Room Join driver is intended for use by Hospitality systems. It allows events to occur across multiple hotel rooms. Because the hotel rooms are controlled by separate instances of Director, this functionality is not normally possible.

The rooms are not joined in the sense that they can see and control items from all rooms in Navigator. Rather, they are "joined" only in that an event can be triggered in one room and then propogated to other rooms. For example, a keypad button press in one room can signal that the lights be turned off in all rooms.

The driver has a set of 20 commands. Executing one of these commands causes one of 20 corresponding events to be dispatched in all the joined rooms, and the associated programming to be executed. The event will also be dispatched in the originating room if the parameter of the command is set to the value called "Dispatch event in: joined rooms and locally".

The Hospitality server joins rooms when a check-in event occurs that signals that the rooms should be joined. A hotel guest can't cause the rooms to be joined. You may join rooms for testing purposes by executing code in the Lua Command window as long as care is taken to disjoin the rooms afterward. Join the rooms using a comma-delimited list of IP addresses (or host names) as the ROOMS parameter of the JOIN_ROOMS command, like this:

ExecuteCommand("JOIN_ROOMS", {["ROOMS"]="192.168.1.100,192.168.1.103"})

Disjoin the rooms by executing the UNJOIN command:

ExecuteCommand("UNJOIN")

Don't join a room to itself.</documentation>

